s that propelled the young Cid’s unparalleled popularity. The book traces this vibrant narrative tradition from its earliest manifestation in the aftermath of Charlemagne’s imperial mission in Spain to the early modern drama of Guillén de Castro. It convincingly discerns the leadership qualities and the social impact of its legendary protagonists, from their manifestation in the Latin chronicles of early Iberia through the Renaissance, incorporating a wealth of previous scholarship in its innovative findings. Speaking Truth to Power provides readers with a heightened appreciation for the vibrancy of the poetic tradition that lives beyond the texts we study, the oral narratives that are continually refashioned for new audiences and contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aCrónica de Castilla.  aEl Cid.  aFoucault.  aGuillén de Castro.  aMocedades de Rodrigo.  aMocedades del Cid.  aParrhesia.  aRodrigo Díaz.  aSpanish literature.  aXimena.  aYoung Cid.  aaffect.  aearly modern drama.  amedieval literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079737440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753506340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487535063423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487535063/original  a978-3-11-079737-4  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles